":"–1285","–Male":"Overleden","1225–1286":"1225–1286","1186–Male":"1186–Overleden","1205":"1205","22 April 1269":"22 april 1269","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1286":"1286","1186":"1186","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Beverston, Gloucestershire, England":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Bristol Unitary Authority, Bristol, England":"Bristol, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1205–22 April 1269":"1205–22 April 1269","1205–1269":"1205–1269","–Female":"Deceased","1203–1280":"1203–1280","–1285":"–1285","–Male":"Deceased","1225–1286":"1225–1286","1186–Male":"1186–Deceased","1205":"1205","22 April 1269":"22 April 1269","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1286":"1286","1186":"1186","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Beverston, Gloucestershire, England":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Bristol Unitary Authority, Bristol, England":"Bristol, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gournay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Gourley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gourley","meanings":["Scottish: possibly a Norman habitational name from North or South Gorley (Hampshire), or an unidentified place in Normandy, France."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":10,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":19,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":54,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Gournay II was born in 1205, in Beverston, Gloucestershire, England as the son of Robert de Gournay I. He had at least 1 son with Hawise de Longchamp. He died on 22 April 1269, in his hometown, at the age of 64, and was buried in Bristol, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1205–22 April 1269":"1205–22. aprill 1269","1205–1269":"1205–1269","–Female":"Surnud","1203–1280":"1203–1280","–1285":"–1285","–Male":"Surnud","1225–1286":"1225–1286","1186–Male":"1186–Surnud","1205":"1205","22 April 1269":"22. aprill 1269","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1286":"1286","1186":"1186","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beverston, Gloucestershire, England":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Bristol Unitary Authority, Bristol, England":"Bristol, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1205–22 April 1269":"1205–22. huhtikuuta 1269","1205–1269":"1205–1269","–Female":"Kuollut","1203–1280":"1203–1280","–1285":"–1285","–Male":"Kuollut","1225–1286":"1225–1286","1186–Male":"1186–Kuollut","1205":"1205","22 April 1269":"22. huhtikuuta 1269","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1203":"1203","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1286":"1286","1186":"1186","1285":"1285","1280":"1280","Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Beverston, Gloucestershire, England":"Beverston, Gloucestershire, England","Bristol, Bristol Unitary Authori